<!-- Problem Section -->
<section class="deck-section problem-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="problem-content">
      <p class="eyebrow eyebrow-left">The Problem</p>
      <h2 class="reveal">The standard of care hasn't changed in decades</h2>
      <p class="reveal reveal-delay-1">
        Today, ICU nurses manually measure urine output every hour — a process that is error-prone,
        labour-intensive, and provides data far too late to prevent organ damage. By the time AKI is detected
        through conventional methods, the window for effective intervention has often already closed.
      </p>
      <div class="problem-highlight reveal reveal-delay-2">
        <div class="problem-highlight-item">
          <h4>Manual Measurement</h4>
          <p>Hourly readings by hand. Subjective, inconsistent, and takes nurses away from critical care.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-highlight-item">
          <h4>Late Detection</h4>
          <p>Creatinine-based diagnosis catches AKI hours or days after damage has already begun.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-highlight-item">
          <h4>Preventable Deaths</h4>
          <p>Earlier detection — even by hours — dramatically improves outcomes and reduces mortality.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

